{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778556232,"nonce":"WQblLmJfq/YMTQ2NIV1m8kxhco4=","message":"**Retraction (2026-05-11)** — the MVP as run was a dud. The prior comment misframed what Δv is and what the MVP actually measured.\n\n## What Δv actually is\n\nΔv is the peak forward velocity inflation **between the adversarially-trained model and the baseline (warmup-only) model of the same architecture**, signed and projected on the reach axis. It is a *training-method comparison*, not a test-time perturbation response:\n\n```\nΔv_arch = (peak_v(arch_adversarial) - peak_v(arch_baseline)) / peak_v(arch_baseline)\n```\n\nThe C\u0026S signature `Δv \u003e 0` describes how adversarial training inflates peak velocity for a given architecture, relative to that same architecture trained without an adversary. The decoupling-acid-test prediction (regulator → +Δv, tracker → ≈0) says: adversarial training will inflate the regulator's peak velocity but not the tracker's, because the tracker's feedforward channel lets it absorb the disturbance without changing its forward motion plan.\n\n## What the prior MVP actually measured\n\nThe prior MVP trained three controllers without an adversarial phase (warmup-only), then applied a `LinearDynamicsAdversary` perturbation at test time and measured peak-velocity change. That is test-time disturbance response, **not Δv**. It does not test the d448c9d discriminator.\n\n## Implications\n\nThe 'informative null' framing in the prior comment was wrong. The MVP did not actually test the regulator-vs-tracker decoupling hypothesis. The numbers reported (regulator +1%/+3.5%/+6%, tracker identical, GRU +0.5%) describe how three warmup-only-trained controllers respond to a test-time disturbance — a different and uninteresting question.\n\n## Corrected MVP design (4 models, not 2)\n\nTo actually test the discriminator, train four models:\n\n1. `linear_regulator_baseline` — warmup-only\n2. `linear_regulator_adversarial` — warmup + adversarial phase\n3. `linear_tracker_baseline` — warmup-only\n4. `linear_tracker_adversarial` — warmup + adversarial phase\n\nThen compute:\n- `Δv_regulator = (peak_v(linear_regulator_adversarial) - peak_v(linear_regulator_baseline)) / peak_v(linear_regulator_baseline)`\n- `Δv_tracker = (peak_v(linear_tracker_adversarial) - peak_v(linear_tracker_baseline)) / peak_v(linear_tracker_baseline)`\n\nDiscriminator outcome: if `Δv_regulator \u003e 0` and `Δv_tracker ≈ 0`, the decoupling-via-parameterisation hypothesis is supported.\n\nThe implementation work (Component subclasses, training-loop dispatch, etc.) is preserved by the original commit `20ae797` and is still usable as-is — only the analysis and the launch protocol need to change. Adding the adversarial-phase runs roughly doubles compute (still tractable on laptop CPU at MVP scale — each adversarial phase is small).","files":null}]}